<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,152,576]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,405,431]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liu &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2020" box="[565,646,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Apanteles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amotus">
<emphasis box="[565,646,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">amotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” derives from the Latin, referring to the vannal lobe beyond its widest rather strongly concave.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,152,576]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,477,503]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Chen &amp; Song" authorityName="Chen &amp; Song" authorityYear="2004" box="[604,887,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Apanteles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stictipes">
<emphasis box="[604,726,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">A. stictipes</emphasis>
Chen &amp; Song
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in the following: second submarginal cell of hind wing weakly higher than wide (slightly wider than high in latter); longitudinal trough rather narrow and indistinct (broad and distinct in latter); and ovipositor relatively thin (thick in latter).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
